Machine-Learning-Data-Analysis-Graduate-Intern-technical-task¶

This notebook Walkthroughs my solutin for the regression problem of predicting the percentage of some material properties within a sample. Basically we used the NIR spectral information (our X) to predict some properties percentages (our y).

This notebook consists of four main parts:

1- Loading and exploring the data.

2- Preparing the data.

3- Builing and evaluating the model.

1- Loading and exploring the data.¶

The data used here consinsts of 7 NIR tabular datasets that comes from 7 different scanners that measure the same matrial. And a reference sheet with two reference values columns, we only used one of the reference variables.

Now, we import all the neeeded library for this notebook.

For preprocessing, We used two different methods:

1- Polynomial detrend + SNV¶
2- Data augmentation¶

2.1 SNV + polynomial detrend¶

At this section, We used the Scatter corrections technique to preprocess our data. We preprocessed the data by applying a Standard Normal Variate (SNV) andsecond order polynomial detrend.

The purpose is to remove instrumental noise, and reduce the variance of the spectra from sources such as scatter effect to improve robustness of the model. Here is a quick summary of what these two preprocessing steps are doing:

The "detrend" process fits a curve (in this case a 2nd order polynomial) to the spectra and subtracts it from the spectra. This usually centers the spectra around zero and eliminates small/known spectral distortions.

SNV stands for Standard Normal Variate and consists in finding the mean value for each spectrum and subtract it from the spectrum followed by a division by the standard deviation of that spectrum (i.e. these operations are done on a single spectrum (single row), not over many samples. SNV transforms the data in each spectrum as being centered on zero with std = 1.

For the detrend we used the detrend function implemented by the obspy.signal.detrend package.

This function performs detrend on the data directly (in place). In order to not modify the original data we had to use copy(). Example of detreind a spectrum:

In [28]:
x_sample_detrended = polynomial(X_train[0].copy(),order=2,plot=True)

So we had to go sample by sample and perform SNV and followed by detrend correction. We created a couple of functions that loop through all samples.

In [29]:
## Define a function to perform Standard Normal Variate on all spectra  
def snv(input_data):
    # Define a new array and populate it with the corrected data  
    data_snv = np.zeros_like(input_data)
    for i in range(input_data.shape[0]):
         # Apply correction
        data_snv[i,:] = (input_data[i,:] - np.mean(input_data[i,:])) / np.std(input_data[i,:])
    return data_snv

## Define a function detrend all spectra
def det(input_data):
    data_det = np.zeros_like(input_data)
    for i in range(input_data.shape[0]):
        # Apply detrend
        data_det[i,:] = polynomial(input_data[i,:].copy(), order=2, plot=False)
    return data_det

Performing detrending followed by SNV was not recommended by Barnes et al. Standard Normal Variate Transformation and De-trending of Near-Infrared Diffuse Reflectance Spectra, So we applied SNV followed by detrending.

2.2 Data Augmentation¶

Instead of correction of the baseline variations we use a special implementation of data augmentation. The idea is to simulate the expected form of irrelevant noise (here baseline offset and slope and overall spectrum intensity), and expect the model to either extract features robust to the variations, or figure out the best corrections during training. This way we can make more efficient use of the labelled dataset. The idea is similar to the image rotations and croppings done in image recognition training.

In [31]:
#Expand dataset, Function also available in ChemUtils
def dataaugment(X, betashift = 0.05, slopeshift = 0.05,multishift = 0.05):
    #Shift of baseline
    #calculate arrays
    beta = np.random.random(size=(X.shape[0],1))*2*betashift-betashift
    slope = np.random.random(size=(X.shape[0],1))*2*slopeshift-slopeshift + 1
    #Calculate relative position
    axis = np.array(range(X.shape[1]))/float(X.shape[1])
    #Calculate offset to be added
    offset = slope*(axis) + beta - axis - slope/2. + 0.5

    #Multiplicative
    multi = np.random.random(size=(X.shape[0],1))*2*multishift-multishift + 1

    X = multi*X + offset

    return X

To illustrate what data augmentation does, we augmented the first spectrum.

3- Builing and evaluating the model.¶

At the heart of all regression methods is the idea of correlating measured spectra of a substance to be analysed, with known reference values of the same substance. In this way one can build a calibration model that translates the spectrum into the value of interest. A robust calibration will then enable to obtain the value (or values) of interest straight form the spectra. Here we used PLS model. Partial Least Squares (PLS) regression is the most widely used technique for developing NIR calibrations.

PLS uses several factors to reach the optimum models which can be helpful in a physical interpretation of the sources of correlation between x and y variables. As NIR data needs to be calibrated against primary reference data of the parameter one seeks to measure, PLS is a good choice.

we want to run a PLS regression with a variable number of components and test its performance in cross-validation. In practice we want to find the number of components that minimises the MSE. We wrote optimise_pls_cv function to do that.

This function first runs a loop over the number of PLS components and calculates the MSE of prediction. Secondly, it finds the number of components that minimises the MSE and uses that value to run a PLS again. A bunch of metrics (R2 score, RMSE and Standard deviations of prediction errors(SEP)) is calculated and printed to evaluate the model with some plots to illustrate the model performance on trainging and testing data.

In [34]:
def optimise_pls_cv(X, y, x_test, y_test,n_comp, plot_components=True):
 
    '''Run PLS including a variable number of components, up to n_comp,
       and calculate MSE '''
 
    mse = []
    component = np.arange(1, n_comp)
 
    for i in component:
        pls = PLSRegression(n_components=i)
 
        # Cross-validation
        y_cv = cross_val_predict(pls, X, y, cv=5)
 
        mse.append(mean_squared_error(y, y_cv))
 
        comp = 100*(i+1)/n_comp
        # Trick to update status on the same line
        stdout.write("\r%d%% completed" % comp)
        stdout.flush()
    stdout.write("\n")
 
    # Calculate and print the position of minimum in MSE
    msemin = np.argmin(mse)
    print("Suggested number of components: ", msemin+1, "with MSE value of", round(np.min(mse), 2))
    stdout.write("\n")
 
    if plot_components is True:
        with plt.style.context(('ggplot')):
            plt.plot(component, np.array(mse), '-v', color = 'blue', mfc='blue')
            plt.plot(component[msemin], np.array(mse)[msemin], 'P', ms=10, mfc='red')
            plt.xlabel('Number of PLS components')
            plt.ylabel('MSE')
            plt.title('PLS')
            plt.xlim(left=-1)
 
        plt.show()
 
    # Define PLS object with optimal number of components
    pls_opt = PLSRegression(n_components=msemin+1)
 
    # Fit to the entire dataset
    pls_opt.fit(X, y)
    # use best model on test set
    y_pred = pls_opt.predict(x_test)

    y_c = pls_opt.predict(X)
 
    # Cross-validation
    y_cv = cross_val_predict(pls_opt, X, y, cv=5)
 

 
     ## Compute test error scores
    score_p = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
    mse_p = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)
    rmse_p = np.sqrt(mse_p)
    sep = np.std(y_test - y_pred)
    
    ## Compute train error scores 
    score_p0 = r2_score(y, y_c)
    mse_p0 = mean_squared_error(y, y_c)
    rmse_p0 = np.sqrt(mse_p0)
    sep0 = np.std(y - y_c)
  
    print('ERROR METRICS: \t TRAIN \t\t TEST')
    print('--------------------------------------')
    print('R2: \t\t %5.3f \t\t %5.3f'  % (score_p0, score_p ))
    print('RMSE: \t\t %5.3f \t\t %5.3f' % (rmse_p0, rmse_p))
    print('SEP : \t\t %5.3f \t\t %5.3f' % (sep0, sep))
    
    print(r2_score(pls_opt.predict(x_test), y_test))
    # Fit a line to the training data response
    z = np.polyfit(y, y_c, 1)
    with plt.style.context(('ggplot')):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 5))
        ax.scatter(y_c, y, c='red', edgecolors='k')
        #Plot the best fit line
        ax.plot(np.polyval(z,y), y, c='blue', linewidth=1)
        plt.title('$Training, R^{2}$: '+str(score_p0))
        plt.xlabel('Predicted')
        plt.ylabel('Measured')
 
        plt.show()
        
    # Fit a line to the testing data response
    z = np.polyfit(y_test, y_pred, 1)
    with plt.style.context(('ggplot')):
        fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(9, 5))
        ax.scatter(y_pred, y_test, c='red', edgecolors='k')
        #Plot the best fit line
        ax.plot(np.polyval(z,y_test), y_test, c='blue', linewidth=1)
        plt.title('$Testing, R^{2}$: '+str(score_p))
        plt.xlabel('Predicted')
        plt.ylabel('Measured')
 
        plt.show()
    return pls_opt

Test-Time Augmentation¶

Data augmentation is an approach typically used during the training of the model that expands the training set with modified copies of samples from the training dataset. That's why we didn't apply it to test set. But it may be a good idea to try and use it on test data too!

Augmentations are chosen to give the model the best opportunity for correctly predicting the target value for given input, and the number of copies of an input sample for which a model must make a prediction is often small, such as less than 10 or 20. So we defined a function do Test-Time Augmentation (TTA). The idea is, for each single input instance we augment it with factor of 10 and feed the 10 samples to the model and calculate the mean of the 10 predictions.

In [166]:
# make a prediction using test-time augmentation
def TTA_prediction(Data, model, n_examples):
    predictions = []
    # Loop over all the passed data
    for sample in Data: 
        #Repeating the spectrum 
        sample = np.repeat(sample.reshape(1, -1), repeats=n_examples, axis=0)
        # Augmenting the spectrum
        sample_aug = dataaugment(sample,betashift = 0.01, slopeshift = 0.005,multishift = 0.1)
        # make predictions for each augmented spectrum
        y_pred = model.predict(sample_aug)
        # mean of predictions
        m = np.mean(y_pred, axis=0)
        
        predictions.append(m)

    return np.array(predictions)
